TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Coercive Isomorphism Ripple Effect: An Investigation of Nonprofit Interlocks on Corporate Boards
AU  - Krause, Ryan
AU  - Wu, Zhiyan
AU  - Bruton, Garry D.
AU  - Carter, Suzanne M.
Y1  - 2018/05/04
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2019/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2017.0064
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2017.0064
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 283
EP  - 308
VL  - 62
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Institutional theorists have long recognized that board interlocks serve as conduits of information, which can facilitate mimetic isomorphism under conditions of uncertainty. In contrast, the potential for coercive isomorphism?which is a response to direct coercion rather than uncertainty?to spread through board interlocks remains unknown. Drawing on the forced compliance literature from social psychology, we propose that coercive isomorphism exhibits a ripple effect, whereby conforming to coercive pressures leads directors to internalize their acquiescence and apply it to the other boards on which they sit. We test this relationship in the context of nonprofit interlocks on the boards of 209 publicly traded U.S. firms between 2010 and 2014, predicting that coercive pressure to minimize overhead in the nonprofit sphere?a phenomenon known as the nonprofit starvation cycle?spreads to corporate boards through nonprofit interlocks, leading the corporate boards to reduce firm investment in intangible assets. We find that this relationship manifests across our sample, but is strongest via interlocks held by powerful directors and in industries characterized by high investment in intangible assets. Finally, we also find that the coercive isomorphism ripple effect ultimately decreases firm value.
AB  - Institutional theorists have long recognized that board interlocks serve as conduits of information, which can facilitate mimetic isomorphism under conditions of uncertainty. In contrast, the potential for coercive isomorphism?which is a response to direct coercion rather than uncertainty?to spread through board interlocks remains unknown. Drawing on the forced compliance literature from social psychology, we propose that coercive isomorphism exhibits a ripple effect, whereby conforming to coercive pressures leads directors to internalize their acquiescence and apply it to the other boards on which they sit. We test this relationship in the context of nonprofit interlocks on the boards of 209 publicly traded U.S. firms between 2010 and 2014, predicting that coercive pressure to minimize overhead in the nonprofit sphere?a phenomenon known as the nonprofit starvation cycle?spreads to corporate boards through nonprofit interlocks, leading the corporate boards to reduce firm investment in intangible assets. We find that this relationship manifests across our sample, but is strongest via interlocks held by powerful directors and in industries characterized by high investment in intangible assets. Finally, we also find that the coercive isomorphism ripple effect ultimately decreases firm value.
